d=http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/images/bar.jpg class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1659<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/16/02 4:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  What if the Germans had won WWII?</span><hr size=1> Where would the world be today technologically?<br>
<br>
Would the world's two super powers be The Greater German Reich and Imperial Japan (instead of USA and USSR). Would a similar cold war competition have ensued?<br>
<br>
What could Wernher Von Braun have accomplished if his work had continued uninterupted?  Would we have seen Germans walking on the moon by the late 1950's?  Maybe on Mars by the late 60's?<br>
<br>
Assuming the world wasn't destroyed in a nuclear exchange. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 561<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/16/02 11:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What if the Germans had won WWII?</span><hr size=1> I sometimes wonder if Hitler might have built up his navy and then turned on Japan in a grab for China if the Axis had won the initial war.  Considering Hitler's awful racial policies and the need to find enemies to focus on in order to keep people from turning on the oppressive Nazi government I don't think the Japanese would have been considered allies for long.  Just consider how Hitler had accepted Stalin as an ally until it no longer suited him.  One thing is for sure though, it would not have been a friendly world for Jews and people of various races.  Just out of curiosity though I wonder who would have won if the Japanese and the Germans did go at each other's throat.  The Japanese would have control of China's resources and the Germans those of Russia.  I think one of the two nations would have developed nukes and made mincemeat of the world.  As for Werhner Von Braun, I sometimes wonder if Hitler would have allowed the creation of a civilian space program that didn't have weaponization in mind.  I believe Von Braun would still have been developing rockets for military use at least.   <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=joestalin@nuclearspace>JoeStalin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 77<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/18/02 4:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  ...</span><hr size=1> Don't you think that the Germinization of space would have been a rather exciting idea for the Nazis?  It'd be like throwing German blood out into the final frontier, making it truly theirs.  Glorification of the race and all that.<br>
<br>
Bah, I don't know.<br>
<br>
Certainly, if the allies lost the war, affirmative action would never have been a problem.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=joestalin@nuclearspace>JoeStalin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 78<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/18/02 4:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  ...</span><hr size=1> Or perhaps they'd have their own version of it.  I don't really know much about politics in Nazi Germany.  It must be a terribly fascinating subject.  All a person is used to hearing is that Hitler was the devil and all that jazz. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 567<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/18/02 5:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: ...</span><hr size=1> A good book to read about Nazi Germany is &quot;The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich&quot; by William Shirer.  Took me all summer to read that thing--all 2000 pages of nano sized print.  I hadn't thought about the propaganda possibilities inherent in fostering a space program though.  I can see how the Nazi's would have fostered a space program as a means of displaying their might.  It'd be the same type of attitude that motivated the USA and Russia in the space race.  At the least it would give the Nazis something to do as they rearmed themselves for more war until they owned the whole planet.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1667<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/18/02 6:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Von Braun would have pushed for a space station first.  Maybe the<br>
A9/10 would have launched around 1947-50, putting the first man in <br>
space a full decade earlier than real history.  A manned space station<br>
would have been of interest to the German military to keep an eye on<br>
Japan, and to possibly serve as a weapons platform.  The ability<br>
to drop a nuke on your enemy from orbit would reduce the amount<br>
of warning time to impact too.  The first German station may have<br>
gone up around 1955-60.<br>
<br>
Now for the big question in this alternate history... would the Germans<br>
develop an Orion type vehicle and ground launch it?  I seriously<br>
doubt that a nuclear test ban treaty would have been signed<br>
with Japan.  The Nazis had a tight control over everything.  There <br>
was very little room for public opinion.<br>
<br>
So let's assume they succssfully launch a NPR around 1965-70.<br>
As soon as they place a few NPR's in space, they would own the<br>
planet.  If anyone is crazy enough to use nukes in a first strike<br>
against another nuclear power it would have been the Nazi government.<br>
<br>
So shortly after placing a few Orion type vehicles is space by<br>
the Nazis a massive nuclear war would trash much of Asia and Europe.<br>
<br>
The end.<br>
<br>
