ace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=drcarstairs>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 141<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/21/02 6:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.imgstudio.com/2002/March/28/stamp_lthumb/032820021216063.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Actually, Hitler had some super weapons</span><hr size=1> But as the war plodded on, he cut funding for projects that had long-term development times in favor of those that looked like they could be done sooner.<br>
<br>
Germany had a functional Jet at the end of the war, but I guess their infrastructure was already too mangled for that to be of use. If they could have turned them out in number, it certainly would have prolonged the war.<br>
<br>
I don’t think Heisenberg was as close as he has said he was.   <br>
<br>
I think the Japanese were concentrating on bio-weapons. I saw something about them releasing a super-bubonic plague in Manchuria (<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.fas.org/nuke/guide/japan/bw/" target="top">Japans Biological Weapons Program </a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->). I don’t know the state of their nuclear program.<br>
<br>
Certainly Germany and Japan would have turned on each other in the end, just as the US and USSR did. I wonder if it would have been a cold war, or a hot one. Either way, it would have been nasty.   <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
